And that's why it takes us so long to become liberated.

210
00:23:40,471 --> 00:23:46,963
I mean, if it were just a matter of seeing the way things are, well, we can find how we do it.

211
00:23:47,003 --> 00:23:52,213
It's just, unfortunately, we've got to purify the heart.

212
00:23:52,233 --> 00:23:55,500
So it's known also as the path of purification.

213
00:23:55,519 --> 00:23:56,501
And that's what we read.

214
00:24:01,932 --> 00:24:03,714
This is the path to purification.

215
00:24:04,336 --> 00:24:10,865
So remember that this avijja is normally understood as a wrong understanding.

216
00:24:11,727 --> 00:24:14,351
So that's of course coming from the point of view of wisdom.

217
00:24:15,053 --> 00:24:23,526
And this process is moving us away from that not knowing and the delusion towards wisdom.

218
00:24:23,885 --> 00:24:28,192
But remember that from the heart's point of view, we start from the point of innocence.

219
00:24:28,814 --> 00:24:33,181
There was no time that we really, really meant to do harm.

220
00:24:34,042 --> 00:24:41,115
We might have done so, but fundamentally, there wasn't any real desire to do harm.

221
00:24:41,675 --> 00:24:47,445
It was always to do with this self-protection and this crimped sort of love.

222
00:24:47,605 --> 00:24:54,196
Even when you think of people like, you know, Stalin or Hitler and all that, they did actually love it.

223
00:24:54,598 --> 00:24:55,400
their people.

224
00:24:55,460 --> 00:24:59,084
Hitler loved his dog, things like that.

225
00:24:59,744 --> 00:25:00,826
He wasn't capable of it.

226
00:25:00,846 --> 00:25:01,646
It was just crimped.

227
00:25:01,666 --> 00:25:02,868
It was just torn.

228
00:25:02,989 --> 00:25:06,874
It was just brought into this very specific definition.

229
00:25:07,294 --> 00:25:09,016
And of course, everything else was their enemy.

230
00:25:13,320 --> 00:25:23,913
So, remember that when we talk about Abidjan, and it does come across in the literature as being wrong understanding, which is true.

231
00:25:24,281 --> 00:25:32,994
and the Eightfold Path begins with wrong understanding, remember it also referring to the heart in terms of innocence.

232
00:25:33,015 --> 00:25:46,796
And even though we create all these mistakes, and we've got all these problems, emotional problems, etc., and all that, and we mess people up and everything else, we're heading towards that original purity.

233
00:25:47,557 --> 00:25:50,521
So it's from innocence to purity.

234
00:25:51,063 --> 00:25:52,365
And when that purity...

235
00:25:52,597 --> 00:26:00,249
is conjoined with right understanding, that's when you have proper compassion, love and joy.

236
00:26:00,709 --> 00:26:06,557
That's how it expresses itself through this medium, through this psychophysical organism.

237
00:26:06,678 --> 00:26:11,423
It expresses itself that way.

238
00:26:11,443 --> 00:26:19,576
So going back to this Dependent Frigination, which is only describing how we create suffering.

239
00:26:20,076 --> 00:26:21,238
So we've got this point

240
00:26:25,369 --> 00:26:26,090
I want.

241
00:26:27,051 --> 00:26:31,778
Now, in our language, the I always comes first, right?

242
00:26:31,798 --> 00:26:34,842
So, I want a cup of tea.

243
00:26:35,442 --> 00:26:36,544
I want to go here.

244
00:26:37,163 --> 00:26:43,352
So, from the language point of view, from our personal experience point of view, this I always comes first.

245
00:26:44,073 --> 00:26:50,160
If the I always came first, there would be actually no escape.

246
00:26:52,262 --> 00:26:53,284
The identity

247
00:26:53,634 --> 00:27:03,409
draws us into a connection, an inner connection with something from which there's no escape.

248
00:27:03,630 --> 00:27:08,115
Once you've said I and you've empowered it, that's it, you've done it.

249
00:27:08,557 --> 00:27:14,665
You've created something, an action of speech, of thought, or of the body.

250
00:27:15,487 --> 00:27:23,018
So it's because, and this is for me such a crucial insight that the Buddha had, it's because the I

251
00:27:23,268 --> 00:27:26,990
comes after the process, or in the middle of the process, that the escape happens.

252
00:27:28,211 --> 00:27:36,378
Otherwise, see, if it were pleasant feeling, I want pleasant feeling, there'd be no escape.

253
00:27:36,919 --> 00:27:43,265
It's the fact that there is, first of all, the wanting that allows us to see where the escape is.

254
00:27:43,944 --> 00:27:45,365
And then there's the I want.

255
00:27:46,607 --> 00:27:48,308
And then, of course, there's the empowerment.

256
00:27:48,729 --> 00:27:53,173
So, if you were to say something like, you're passing something like a coffee shop,

257
00:27:53,676 --> 00:27:57,102
And you say to yourself, you know, I'd like a cup of coffee.

258
00:27:57,182 --> 00:28:05,694
If you go back on that, in the proper process of psychology, it would be smelling, seeing, coffee.

259
00:28:06,115 --> 00:28:06,935
There's your contact.

260
00:28:07,678 --> 00:28:08,878
There would be pleasant.

261
00:28:09,400 --> 00:28:10,481
Very pleasant.

262
00:28:11,502 --> 00:28:13,306
Then there'd be wanting.

263
00:28:14,007 --> 00:28:16,309
And then there'd be I want.

264
00:28:17,030 --> 00:28:18,492
And then you'd be into the shop.

265
00:28:18,753 --> 00:28:19,914
You'd be in there buying coffee.

266
00:28:21,156 --> 00:28:21,657
So it's

267
00:28:28,979 --> 00:28:30,540
Coffee smell.

268
00:28:31,060 --> 00:28:31,862
Pleasant smell.

269
00:28:32,162 --> 00:28:34,503
That's the contact.

270
00:28:34,523 --> 00:28:35,204
Coffee smell.

271
00:28:36,306 --> 00:28:37,847
Pleasant coffee smell.

272
00:28:38,407 --> 00:28:40,130
Want pleasant coffee smell.

273
00:28:40,971 --> 00:28:42,952
I want pleasant coffee.

274
00:28:43,692 --> 00:28:45,174
I get pleasant coffee.

275
00:28:45,194 --> 00:28:47,196
So there's an empowerment of that desire.

276
00:28:48,637 --> 00:28:52,521
So that's how the actual process is working all the time, you see.

277
00:28:52,541 --> 00:28:54,084
And that's why there's this escape.

278
00:28:54,544 --> 00:28:57,287
But to see that escape, you've got to be completely awake.

279
00:28:57,386 --> 00:28:58,647
You've got to be aware of it.

280
00:28:58,932 --> 00:29:00,834
So we all know it's there, you see.

281
00:29:01,374 --> 00:29:11,742
So in our daily lives, the idea is to maintain that sort of mindfulness so that we're quickly at the point before we become identified with it.

282
00:29:12,423 --> 00:29:18,729
And this can be difficult in sort of areas where you're irritated by somebody.

283
00:29:18,868 --> 00:29:22,291
You see, normally speaking, you'd be out there quick, you know.

284
00:29:23,553 --> 00:29:27,977
But if we're there and we can feel that irritation growing in us,

285
00:29:28,192 --> 00:29:34,711
We can sort of hold it, you see, hold it there for a second and raise the attention towards what the person is saying.

286
00:29:35,614 --> 00:29:37,558
So we're stopping that reaction.

287
00:29:37,960 --> 00:29:40,508
And if you stop the reaction, you stop the identity.

288
00:29:40,909 --> 00:29:41,509
Yeah.

289
00:29:41,529 --> 00:29:43,536
And when you go home, you make an effort.

290
00:29:52,982 --> 00:29:57,990
So once we see that process, it re-empowers us.

291
00:29:58,290 --> 00:30:00,815
It gives us our power back, you see.

292
00:30:03,159 --> 00:30:10,471
So those, now, the next point of interest, apart from this, is translated as grasping, by the way.

293
00:30:10,971 --> 00:30:11,952
That's how it's translated.

294
00:30:12,413 --> 00:30:18,804
So it's craving, which is, you know, obviously doesn't, what the word craving is telling us is that it's a wrong desire.

295
00:30:19,444 --> 00:30:20,626
But it's two stronger words.

296
00:30:22,260 --> 00:30:26,866
tiny desire to something that is overwhelmingly desired.

297
00:30:27,547 --> 00:30:29,470
And then there's this process of identity.

298
00:30:30,150 --> 00:30:32,212
And the next one, the next word is bhava.

299
00:30:32,553 --> 00:30:35,195
So this translates as becoming.

300
00:30:36,198 --> 00:30:40,843
So at that point, the self keeps on recreating itself.

301
00:30:40,863 --> 00:30:44,488
So remember that process isn't a sort of one-off thing.

302
00:30:44,567 --> 00:30:48,092
It's constantly going over and over and over throughout the day.

303
00:30:48,372 --> 00:30:50,714
So there are some times when it's not happening.

304
00:30:51,218 --> 00:30:57,506
So if you're just resting and you're being silent, then that dependent origination isn't working.

305
00:30:57,885 --> 00:31:02,491
It's only working when that desire comes up, or the aversion, the opposite.

306
00:31:03,792 --> 00:31:14,226
So at the bhava, there's the becoming, there's three things, there's the becoming, and there's the will that allows something to be manifest.

307
00:31:15,146 --> 00:31:19,352
And in the Buddha's understanding, the action and the will are the same thing.

308
00:31:19,720 --> 00:31:28,648
So just in ordinary physics, as far as I understand, when you throw a stone into the air, you cannot separate the force from the stone.

309
00:31:30,971 --> 00:31:32,272
So it's the same with an action.

310
00:31:32,313 --> 00:31:35,796
You cannot separate the will from the action that you're performing.

311
00:31:36,636 --> 00:31:41,281
If you were to withdraw your will, then the action would stop.

312
00:31:43,044 --> 00:31:46,487
So at that point there, there's a few things happening.

313
00:31:54,027 --> 00:32:22,971
produces a consequence so the consequence is the beginning of the action the process of the action and the ending of it now that dependent origination is also posited as a three life process but for us it makes much more sense if we actually reduce it to moment to moment moment to moment experience so there it is underlying every moment of our lives is this delusion right

314
00:32:23,508 --> 00:32:31,719
Even if we have an inkling of it, even if we're aware of it in some way, it still remains as a habit of identity.

315
00:32:32,420 --> 00:32:39,829
And on all these habits, all these programs running underneath this little being.

316
00:32:39,849 --> 00:32:46,259
And then you have a moment where some information comes in.

317
00:32:46,298 --> 00:32:50,223
So it could be information from the outside, you hear something.

318
00:32:50,727 --> 00:32:58,656
or it's an information coming from inside, some thought, some emotion comes up with a line or something.

319
00:32:59,518 --> 00:33:08,970
And as soon as that happens, then the reaction comes in, the identity comes in, the empowerment comes in, and the whole process turns over.

320
00:33:09,309 --> 00:33:11,773
And every time it does that, it makes things worse.

321
00:33:11,794 --> 00:33:13,115
Every time it does that, it makes things worse.

322
00:33:13,935 --> 00:33:19,282
And if we can just stop it at the point of reaction, that's when the whole thing collapses.

323
00:33:20,241 --> 00:33:22,003
So there's two points of collapse.

324
00:33:22,765 --> 00:33:36,301
That one there, to recognize when desire is there and to allow the desire to exhaust itself, which drains this underlying habit of its power.

325
00:33:36,321 --> 00:33:46,414
So if we work on, say, a habit that we don't want and we keep working on it and we keep draining it of power, eventually the habit runs, but we're not fooled by it.

326
00:33:46,454 --> 00:33:47,936
We're not sucked into it.

327
00:33:48,742 --> 00:33:55,173
And it's often a good thing to go for the big one, because if you go for the big one, it seems to drain all the others too.

328
00:33:55,213 --> 00:34:06,032
Because all the time we're growing in that sort of spiritual energy of not being caught up in things that are unwholesome for us.

329
00:34:06,054 --> 00:34:09,099
And the other point is the Savicca, you see.

330
00:34:09,119 --> 00:34:11,443
So, recognizing that

331
00:34:21,244 --> 00:34:27,077
That's how you know that it's activated, that it's there within us.

332
00:34:28,280 --> 00:34:37,161
And this sense of self, I think we went through it this morning about this identity that if you bite your tongue just for one moment, you are the body.

333
00:34:37,702 --> 00:34:39,186
That's what we mean by identity.

334
00:34:40,043 --> 00:34:48,030
And the most subtlest form of identity is this position that we take when we are practicing Vipassana.

335
00:34:48,570 --> 00:34:56,498
So here, we have, whether we are aware of it or not, we've pulled ourselves out of the whole psychophysical organism.

336
00:34:56,898 --> 00:35:06,068
We found a place within us, which one writer calls, a great book to read, by the way, still, it's one of the

337
00:35:10,199 --> 00:35:37,657
in time which he calls the observation post so you found this place up here usually just behind you just behind the forehead where you are centered where you are positioned and you're able to observe and feel everything that's being offered from that position as an object now as soon as something is an object you can't be it

338
00:35:38,396 --> 00:35:41,481
That's an important thing to keep hammering home.

339
00:35:42,141 --> 00:35:49,010
Even when you're there just sitting by yourself and you get a pain in the knee, you say, there's a pain in it, not my knee, there's a pain in it.

340
00:35:49,811 --> 00:35:53,615
And you point to it and you say, well, it's down there and this is up here.

341
00:35:54,096 --> 00:35:58,802
That separation, that distance is disidentified.

342
00:36:02,291 --> 00:36:05,255
And you can do that with emotions, you can do that with thought.

343
00:36:06,175 --> 00:36:13,483
Now this isn't the disidentification that comes from mental illness because that just causes confusion.

344
00:36:14,103 --> 00:36:18,748
What this should do is ground you in the observer, the position of the observer.

345
00:36:20,349 --> 00:36:26,454
So you're more grounded in that ability to observe, to feel and to know what's going on.

346
00:36:27,737 --> 00:36:31,320
Now even that is a delusive self.

347
00:36:31,552 --> 00:36:33,416
Because, how do you know that?

348
00:36:33,476 --> 00:36:36,119
Because you're aware of being the observer.

349
00:36:37,382 --> 00:36:40,646
If you're aware of being the observer, you can't be that either.

350
00:36:40,666 --> 00:36:43,030
Everything you're aware of, you can't be.

351
00:36:43,972 --> 00:36:46,896
So you have to go even one step beyond that.

352
00:36:47,235 --> 00:36:50,320
But here we come across a real difficulty.

353
00:36:50,702 --> 00:36:58,572
Because as soon as you try and get rid of the observer, you create another person who's trying to get rid of it.

354
00:36:58,592 --> 00:37:01,036
So we're into a real deep paradox.

355
00:37:01,422 --> 00:37:07,166
So here's where the Buddha's teaching is, shall we say, at its most clear.

356
00:37:07,507 --> 00:37:10,489
You don't worry about that at all, right?

357
00:37:10,510 --> 00:37:14,994
You just keep pointing your attention to what you're actually experiencing.

358
00:37:15,835 --> 00:37:22,402
And then when the time is ripe, there is an experience of just pure awareness.

359
00:37:23,262 --> 00:37:30,349
And at that point, the person knows this is the real, everything else is not the real, okay?

360
00:37:32,572 --> 00:37:57,112
So that process of not identifying, what you can do, I was talking to somebody today, what you can do in your meditation is when you're very calm, when you're very peaceful, everything's very still, the mind's not wandering all over the place, and you have this very clear identity of the observer,

361
00:37:59,945 --> 00:38:12,018
That image of the observer, the feeling of the observer, is actually also coming up on this mirror, on this screen of consciousness.

362
00:38:13,601 --> 00:38:14,382
That's what's happening.

363
00:38:14,442 --> 00:38:21,831
So the awareness itself is becoming aware of itself because it feels its own presence on that screen.

364
00:38:23,132 --> 00:38:26,896
And when you look at your face in the mirror, it gives you some idea

365
00:38:35,668 --> 00:38:41,117
If you haven't done the two-mirror trick, then it's always instructive to do it, right?

366
00:38:43,201 --> 00:38:48,889
Where you look in the mirror, you have another mirror looking at the mirror, and that's the one that you look at because it's turned your face around.

367
00:38:49,652 --> 00:38:52,456
And that's where you see how other people see you.

368
00:38:52,516 --> 00:38:54,199
For some people, it's quite a shock.

369
00:38:54,860 --> 00:38:56,782
So, beware.

370
00:39:00,592 --> 00:39:13,367
There's something about the observer, the feeling of somebody observing, which is telling us, there's something that's telling us about the actual awareness itself.

371
00:39:13,387 --> 00:39:24,679
And as it's put in some literature, and this is more Mahayana than Theravada, there's a sort of glancing back into the awareness.

372
00:39:24,699 --> 00:39:27,461
And just ask, and then once you've done it, to ask yourself,

373
00:39:27,744 --> 00:39:29,086
What was there?

374
00:39:29,106 --> 00:39:29,867
What's it made of?

375
00:39:30,409 --> 00:39:32,652
What wasn't there?

376
00:39:32,672 --> 00:39:43,710
And that gives us an inkling that this awareness is something which transcends, is something of a different order to the psychophysical organism that we find ourselves in.

377
00:39:44,911 --> 00:39:55,027
And people who have, for instance, out-of-body experiences, they would know that for sure as a real experience.

378
00:39:55,047 --> 00:39:56,148
So,

379
00:39:58,322 --> 00:40:00,626
And the process of vipassana is sort of helping us.

380
00:40:00,666 --> 00:40:06,391
It's helping us in daily life to see this process of desire and not get caught up in it.

381
00:40:07,132 --> 00:40:20,427
And it's helping us in our sitting to begin to see, to undo, shall we say, the veils of delusion that we've fallen into just by simple mistakes.

382
00:40:21,389 --> 00:40:22,389
Quite understandably so.

383
00:40:43,682 --> 00:40:46,306
you know, reading about it, mulling over it.

384
00:40:47,168 --> 00:40:52,175
But when you sit in vipassana, you forget all that, just put it completely to the side.

385
00:40:52,876 --> 00:41:00,829
And we have to have this clear confidence that this intuitive awareness actually has the power to liberate itself.

386
00:41:01,471 --> 00:41:04,335
And that's really the paradox.

387
00:41:04,355 --> 00:41:05,657
It's the Buddha within that's doing

388
00:41:10,648 --> 00:41:16,556
unveiling and the disappearance of that delusion is the process of awakening.

389
00:41:16,757 --> 00:41:18,300
Awakening to the way things really are.

390
00:41:20,503 --> 00:41:23,226
And that's basically what we're in the process of.

391
00:41:23,646 --> 00:41:26,271
So there's hope, you see, somewhere.

392
00:41:26,710 --> 00:41:26,911
Yes?

393
00:41:29,815 --> 00:41:30,976
So I don't know how we're done.

394
00:41:31,818 --> 00:41:33,320
Oh, it's not so bad.

395
00:41:33,340 --> 00:41:35,003
I can only hope my words have been

396
00:41:37,025 --> 00:41:46,275
not cause even greater confusion and that you will by your practice liberate yourself from all suffering sooner rather than later.

